Fixed. The root cause was in `util.shallowClone`, and the fix is a two-line addition there.

**Root cause:** When you call `.default(value)` with a non-function value, zod exposes it through a `defaultValue` getter (packages/zod/src/v4/core/api.ts:1461) that runs the value through `util.shallowClone` on every access — precisely so each parse gets a fresh copy. But `shallowClone` (packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts:399) only handled plain objects (`{...o}`) and arrays (`[...o]`); anything else, including `Map` and `Set`, was returned by reference. So every parse that hit the default got the *same* Map instance, and mutating the parse output leaked into all later parses — exactly the behavior in the report.

**Fix:** added `Map` and `Set` branches to `shallowClone`:

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  if (o instanceof Map) return new Map(o);
  if (o instanceof Set) return new Set(o);
  return o;
}
```

This is the single choke point — the same getter pattern is used in four places (core `api.ts`, classic and mini `schemas.ts`, for both `.default()` and `.prefault()`), and all of them call `util.shallowClone`, so fixing it here covers every variant.

**Verification:** my repro script now shows each `parse(undefined)` returning a distinct Map/Set (mutating one no longer affects the next parse), for `.default()` and `.prefault()` alike. The full zod test suite passes: 3,680 tests across 326 files, plus the typechecked run of the default/prefault/index suites — no regressions.
